programme.title: Fractured Flickers
programme.desc: Fractured Flickers is a live-action syndicated half-hour television comedy show that was produced by Jay Ward, who is otherwise known for animated cartoons. The pilot film was produced in 1961, but the series wasn't completed until 1963. Twenty-six episodes were produced; they were syndicated by Desilu Productions and played for several years on local stations.

programme.title: McLintock! (1963)
programme.desc: Story of an aging cattle baron and his divorce-minded wife, who walked out on him two years ago without a word of explanation and has been living back East and running in very fancy circles.

programme.title: Will Success Spoil Rock Hunter? (1957)
programme.desc: Advertising gets spoofed during the escapades of a copywriter, who is touted as the world's greatest lover. Tony Randall, Jayne Mansfield, Betsy Drake, Joan Blondell, John Williams. Frank Tashlin directed and wrote. From a George Axelrod play.

programme.title: What a Way to Go! (1964)
programme.desc: A wealthy, four-time widow wants to give away her fortune, believing that it is cursed.

programme.title: Bus Stop (1956)
programme.desc: Adaptation of the William Inge play about a pathetic saloon singer who takes off for L.A. but is pursued by a lovesick Montana cowboy, who kidnaps her to bring her back to his hometown. As the cowboy, Don Murray was nominated for a Best Supporting Actor Oscar.

programme.title: The Seven Year Itch (1955)
programme.desc: Farce about a husband who suffers from a rash of guilty fantasies about his voluptuous new neighbour while his wife and son are away on holiday.

programme.title: Take Her, She's Mine (1963)
programme.desc: After his beatnik daughter, in Paris on an art scholarship, appears on a magazine cover, a respected Board of Education president is asked to resign; and he gets into his own predicaments when he flies to France to insist she come home.

programme.title: The Little Princess (1939)
programme.desc: Shirley Temple in a story about a Victorian waif who haunts British hospitals looking for her father after he is allegedly killed while fighting in the Boer War. An adaptation of the Frances Hodgson Burnett kid-lit classic.

programme.title: Mr. Belvedere Goes to College (1949)
programme.desc: Clifton Webb displays his acid style in this romp about a middle-aged author in need of a college degree. Shirley Temple. Avery: Alan Young. Bill: Tom Drake. Mrs. Chase: Jessie Royce Landis. Elliott Nugent directed.

programme.title: Meet John Doe (1941)
programme.desc: Frank Capra's classic about a down-on-his-luck baseball player who agrees to impersonate a fictional, idealistic "everyman" created by a newspaperwoman to boost circulation, and then finds himself at the center of a political movement.

programme.title: The Razor's Edge (1946)
programme.desc: A disillusioned World War I veteran moves to Paris, where he has his heart broken by the woman he loves when she marries another man for his wealth, so he goes off on a journey of self-fulfillment and to seek out the meaning of life in India.

programme.title: Little Big Man (1970)
programme.desc: How the West was won is recalled by a 121-year-old eyewitness who recounts tales of being raised by the Cheyenne and his days as a con man, pioneer, hermit and gunfighter, before becoming an Indian scout to General Custer and being the only survivor of the battle of Little Big Horn.

programme.title: The Comancheros (1961)
programme.desc: A Texas Ranger runs across a gang of white renegades, called the Comancheros, who are trading guns and other contraband with marauding Comanches from a secret hideout in Mexico. He goes undercover as a partner with a vicious outlaw who is a contact man with the Comancheros and knows the whereabouts of their hideout in Mexico. Director Michael Curtiz's last film.

programme.title: Emperor of the North (1973)
programme.desc: Lee Marvin and Ernest Borgnine play rough in this yarn about a hobo determined to ride a train watched over by a sadistic railroad guard. Cigaret: Keith Carradine. Cracker: Charles Tyner. Hogger: Malcolm Atterbury. Policeman: Simon Oakland. Gray Cat: Elisha Cook. Filmed in Oregon. Directed by Robert Aldrich.

programme.title: Monte Walsh (1970)
programme.desc: Two aging cowboys stand at a crossroads, as the invention of railways and barbed wire eliminate the need for the cowhands of the Old West, and though the two find new opportunities for employment, none offer the freedom of the open prairie. Remade in 2003.

programme.title: Prime Cut (1972)
programme.desc: Melodrama about a Chicago enforcer (Lee Marvin) sent to eliminate a Missouri mobster. Gene Hackman, Sissy Spacek. Weenie: Gregory Walcott. Clarabelle: Angel Tompkins. Violet: Janit Baldwin. Shay: William Morey. Delaney: Clint Ellison. Shaughnessy: Howard Platt. Michael Ritchie directed.

programme.title: Macon County Line (1974)
programme.desc: In 1954 Georgia, a sheriff's wife is brutally murdered, and the blood-thirsty widower suspects two drifters and their hitchhiking friend. The drifters are in the wrong place at the wrong time, and are forced to defend themselves.

programme.title: Ice Castles (1978)
programme.desc: A champion skater's medal hopes are dashed when she is stricken blind, but a relationship with a caring young man helps her realize her dreams.

programme.title: Paper Man (2009)
programme.desc: This quirky comedy-drama centers on a failed writer and a high-school girl who strike up a friendship that lifts his spirits. However, both the writer's wife and his imaginary friend think their relationship is a bad idea.

programme.title: How Green Was My Valley (1941)
programme.desc: An account of early 20th-century life with a hard-working, fun-loving family in a Welsh coal-mining village, where they deal with love, death, union strikes and bullying.

programme.title: Gentleman's Agreement (1947)
programme.desc: The experiences of a journalist who pretends to be Jewish to gather data for an exposé on anti-Semitism, and the hatred he is subjected to that takes its toll on his personal life.

programme.title: The Undefeated (1969)
programme.desc: Feuding Union and Confederate Generals who battled each other during the Civil War clash again as they each lead a different group of people out west, but eventually work together when attacked by Mexicans.

programme.title: Flaming Star (1960)
programme.desc: Don Siegel directed this tale of Indian-white antagonism, featuring a surprisingly effective Elvis Presley as the half-Indian son of Dolores Del Rio and John McIntire. Barbara Eden, Steve Forrest. Dred: Karl Swenson. Buffalo Horn: Rudolph Acosta. Doc: Ford Rainey. Angus: Richard Jaeckel.

programme.title: Bandolero! (1968)
programme.desc: A man poses as a preacher to free his outlaw brother from the hangman's noose.

programme.title: Something Big (1971)
programme.desc: Tongue-in-cheek action yarn about a plot to steal a Mexican bandit's treasure trove. Dean Martin, Brian Keith, Honor Blackman. Dover: Carol White. Jesse: Ben Johnson. Johnny: Albert Salmi. Tommy: Don Knight. Polly: Joyce Van Patten. Junior: Denver Pyle. Fitzsimmons: Merlin Olsen. Angel Moon: Robert Donner. Andrew V. McLaglen directed.

programme.title: Rawhide (1951)
programme.desc: Outlaws hole up in an out-of-the-way stagecoach stop while awaiting the arrival of a gold shipment. Meanwhile, the assistant stationmaster plots a means of escape for himself and fellow hostages. To avoid confusion with the TV-Western (1959-65) of the same name, "Rawhide" was retitled "Desperate Siege" for its first television airing in 1962.

programme.title: Duel in the Sun (1946)
programme.desc: Beautiful half-breed Pearl Chavez becomes the ward of her dead father's first love and finds herself torn between her sons, one good and the other bad.

programme.title: North to Alaska (1960)
programme.desc: Prospecting partners in Alaska find gold, prompting one to ask the other if he will escort the man's fiance on a journey to join them.

Travis (Joe Don Baker), to the Congo to determine the whereabouts of his son's missing diamond-hunting team.
